name: Le Mort CD
description: The Day Everything Became Nothing's pulverizing debut from 2003, ‘Le Mort’. Deadly precise drumming, unspeakably downtuned guitar decimation and earth shaking bass fuse into monolithic bulldozing grooves which leave cities flattened rubble in their wake, while the ruptured and twisted sewer lines burp out festering excrement which still sounds far more pleasant than the abhorrent pitch-shifted disgorgements contained on ‘Le Mort’. Track Listing: 1.Revisionist 2.Naked 3.Subtext 4.Horror 5.Method 6.Gravel 7.Industry 8.Blind 9.Protect 10.Mortem

name: Slow Death By Grinding CDep
description: Following on from their ribcage rattling debut “Le Mort”, The Day Everything Became Nothing return with a hammering new EP to fill every one of your orifices with their oozing goregrind stench. “Slow Death By Grinding” (2005), features 3 brand new songs of their mammoth bottom end grinding groove obliteration, a gored up cover of Satyricon’s rock opus “Fuel For Hatred” and a fist pumping ‘live’ track recorded in 2004. Join The Day Everything Became Nothing as they sink lower into the depths of self destruction and submit your useless, feeble, violated body to a Slow Death By Grinding! Track Listing: 1.Fiends Applaud, The Gore Is Over 2.Vin Cerro 3.Nothing But Death 4.Fuel For Hatred (Satyricon cover) 5.Mortem (live)

name: Invention : Destruction CD
description: The Day Everything Became Nothing subject us to their third opus of (sub)sonic aural deconstructivism. “Invention: Destruction” (2006) sees the band resume their melding of the visceral and the mechanical with a massive grinding offensive that is at once rigid and swinging, angular yet fluid. Chugging and winding grooves ooze with booming heaviness over ultra-precise timing and rhythm shifting drumming which stops, starts and doubles back again with pinpoint accuracy and neck snapping rapidity. Taking a militaristically clinical approach to a genre usually defined by looseness and grime, The Day Everything Became Nothing simultaneously destroy and reinvent the gore/groove grind conventions to create a simplistically complex model for widespread devastation. Aided in their mission by guest vocalists from Fuck…I’m Dead, Mors Principium Est and Damaged, The Day Everything Became Nothing’s purging wave of demolition cannot be stopped! Track Listing: 1.In 2.Cut 3.Burn 4.Beat 5.Press 6.Crush 7.Shock 8.Burst 9.Flay 10.Rack 11.Pierce
